Bird Strike Data Analysis¶

by (Ekwunife Mmesoma)¶

Introduction¶

A bird strike can be defined as a collision between a bird and an aircraft that is in flight or on a take-off or landing roll. They are a major problem worldwide because they threaten passenger safety and result in costly repairs and lost revenue for the commercial air carrier.

The dataset used for this analysis contains bird strike cases from 1990 to 2021 in the United States and the bird strike cases that caused damage to the aircraft were 13593 out of 45039 bird strike cases.

Data dictionary¶

AMO: International Civil Aviation Organization code for Aircraft Model

EMA: Engine Make Code

EMO: Engine Model Code

AC_CLASS: Type of aircraft

AC_MASS: 1 = 2,250 kg or less: 2 = ,2251-5700 kg: 3 = 5,701-27,000 kg: 4 = 27,001-272,000 kg: 5 = above 272,000 kg

NUM_ENGS: Number of engines

TYPE_ENG: Type of power A = reciprocating engine (piston): B = Turbojet: C = Turboprop: D = Turbofan: E = None (glider): F = Turboshaft (helicopter): Y = Other

ENG_1_POS: Where engine # 1 is mounted on aircraft

ENG_2_POS: Where engine # 2 is mounted on aircraft

DAY: Day strike occurred

MONTH: Month strike occurred

YEAR: Year strike occurred

TIME_HOUR: Hour in local time

TIME_MIN: Minute in local time

FAAREGION: FAA Region where airport is located

HEIGHT: Feet Above Ground Level

DISTANCE: Nautical miles from airport

PHASE_OF_FLT: Phase of flight during which strike occurred

INGESTED: Engine ingested the bird/ animal

SKY: Type of cloud cover, if any

PRECIP: Precipitation

SPECIES: Common name for bird or other wildlife

INDICATED_DAMAGE: Indicates whether or not aircraft was damaged

SIZE: Size of bird as reported by pilot is a relative scale. Entry should reflect the perceived size as opposed to a scientifically determined value. If more than one species was struck, larger bird is entered.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This dataset contains 45039 bird strike cases with 33 features (Airport, Aircraft, Time_hour, Species, etc.).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of interest in this dataset is Indicated_damage. The Indicated damage feature tells whether the aircraft was damaged or not and so I want to carry out further analysis to find relationship between the Indicated_damage and other variables.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The Species, Time, Season, Airport, State, Distance, Height, Longitude, Latitude, Year and Size would help me in my investigation.

July and August had the most bird strikes which is also the summer (June, July, and August) period.

Question 3: At what time, distance and height do birds strike the most?¶

In [25]:
plt.figure(figsize = [12,15])

#Function for histogram plots
def hist_plot(plot, x, y, df_name, df_var, Xlabel, Ylabel, Title):
    plot
    bin_x = np.arange(x, df_name[df_var].max()+y, y)
    plt.hist(data = df_name, x = df_var, bins = bin_x)
    plt.xlabel(Xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(Ylabel)
    plt.title(Title);
     
hist_plot(plt.subplot(3, 1, 1), 0, 1, bird_strike, 'TIME_HOUR', 'Time in hours', '', 'Distribution of time')

#Function for log hist plots
def feature_log(plot, bin_x, df_name, df_var, tick_x, Xlabel, Ylabel, TITLE):
    plot
    bin_x
    plt.hist(data = df_name, x = df_var, bins = bin_x)
    tick_x
    labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in tick_x]
    plt.xscale('log')
    plt.xticks(tick_x, labels)
    plt.xlabel(Xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(Ylabel)
    plt.title(TITLE)

feature_log(plt.subplot(3, 1, 2), 10 **np.arange(-1, 2+0.1, 0.1), bird_strike, 'DISTANCE', [0.1, 1, 10, 100], 
            'Distance (mi)', '', 'Distribution of distance' )
feature_log(plt.subplot(3, 1, 3), 10 **np.arange(-1, 4.05+0.1, 0.1), bird_strike, 'HEIGHT', [0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000], 
            'Height (ft)', '', 'Distribution of Height' )
#The plots below shows the different distribution of time, distance and height

Observation¶

From the first plot, the bulk of time falls between 8-10 and that is morning while the least time is between 3-4 which is early hours in the morning. The second plot shows that the distance covered mostly by aircrafts lies between 4-5m and the height peaks falls between 3000-4000m. This shows that birds strike mostly in the morning at a distance of 0-20m and height of 3000-4000m.

Question 4: Which Airport and States had the most aircraft damages?¶

plt.figure(figsize = [12, 15])
bird_strike_sub = bird_strike.query('INDICATED_DAMAGE == True')

#Function for barh charts
def feature_sub(plots, df, var, Title):
    plots
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    feature = df[var].value_counts().head(10)
    feature_order = feature.index
    feature_sub = df.loc[df[var].isin(feature_order)]
    sb.countplot(data = feature_sub, y = var, color = default_color, order = feature_order)
    plt.xlabel('')
    plt.title(Title);

feature_sub(plt.subplot(2, 1, 1), bird_strike_sub, 'AIRPORT', 'Top 10 Airports with the most aircraft damages')
feature_sub(plt.subplot(2, 1, 2), bird_strike_sub, 'STATE', 'Top 10 States with the most aircraft damages')
#The plots below shows the different distribution of airports and states with the most aircraft damages

Observation¶

California State, Salt Lake City and Sacramento Intl airport were the states and airports with the most aircraft damages.

#Function for bar plots
def barh_plot(name_df, var_y, Xlabel, Ylabel, Title):
    colors = sb.color_palette()[4]
    sb.countplot(data = name_df, x = var_y, color = colors)
    plt.xlabel(Xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(Ylabel)
    plt.title(Title);
    
barh_plot(bird_strike, 'SIZE', 'Species sizes', '', 'Distribution of species sizes')
#The plot below shows the distribution of species sizes that caused most bird strikes

The longitude distribution is bimodal having its highest peak between -130 and -120 degrees while the latitude distribution is unimodal and left-skewed. From the plot, it can be deduced that at a longitude of -130 to -120 degrees and at a latitude of 40-43 degrees, birds strike the most.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Indicated damage is a categorical variable with two unique values (True and False). True depicts that the aircraft was damaged by bird strike while False depicts that the aircraft was not damaged by bird strike. There were lots of bird strike cases but only 30.2% caused damage to the aircraft.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distance and height feature had very high values and so I scaled the plot using log to account for those values. Also, the aircraft with 2 engines had a very high value counts compared to the other ones (1, 3 and 4).

#Function for adapted barchart
def adapted_barchart(df, var, var_y, m, Title):
    ax = sb.countplot(data = df, x = var, hue = var_y)
    ax.legend(loc = m, framealpha = 1)
    plt.ylabel('')
    plt.title(Title);
    
adapted_barchart(bird_strike, 'INDICATED_DAMAGE', 'SEASON', 1, 'The seasons by Indicated damage')
#The plot below shows the different seasons by indicated damage.

Observation¶

The plot depicts two things:

  • Summer had the most bird strikes while winter had the least.
  • Fall had the most aircraft damages while winter had the least.

In both cases winter had the least bird strikes and aircraft damages.

In [35]:
def Facet_plot(df, var_x, m, var_y):
    bin_edges = np.arange(0, 23+1, 1)
    g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df, col = var_x, col_wrap = m, sharex = False)
    g.map(plt.hist, var_y, bins = bin_edges)
    g.set_xlabels('Time (hr in local time)')
    g.set_titles('{col_name}');
    
Facet_plot(bird_strike, 'MONTH_NAME', 3, 'TIME_HOUR')
#The plot below shows the time distribution across different months of the year

Observation¶

The above plot depicts the following:

  • June, July, August, September, November, and December most frequent time range falls between 8-10 am which is morning.
  • January and February most frequent time range falls between 10-11 am which is also morning.
  • April, October, March, and May time range falls between 22-23 pm which is night.

Question 14: Which bird species caused the most aircraft damage in terms of longitude and latitude?¶

In [37]:
#Function for threshold calculation
def feature_thres(m, df, var_x):
    Threshold = m
    freq = df[var_x].value_counts()
    freq_threshold = np.sum(freq > Threshold)
    feature_index = freq.index[:freq_threshold]
    var_sub = df.loc[df[var_x].isin(feature_index)]
    return var_sub

g = sb.FacetGrid(data = feature_thres(500, bird_strike_sub, 'SPECIES'), hue = 'SPECIES', size = 10)
g.map(sb.regplot, 'LONGITUDE', 'LATITUDE', truncate = False, x_jitter = 0.05, fit_reg = False, scatter_kws = {'alpha':0.7});
font = {'family':'serif','color':'black','weight':'normal','size':16}
g.add_legend()
g.set_xlabels('Latitude (degrees)')
g.set_ylabels('Longitude (degrees)');
plt.title('Top 5 Species that caused aircraft damages in terms longitude and latitude', fontdict = font);
#The plot of longitude and latitude distributions encoded with top five bird species

Observation¶

From the plot above, it can be deduced that at a longitude of -100 to -80 and latitude of 30 to 45 degrees which has bulk of the points, Mourning dove and White-tailed deer caused the most bird strikes.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I found it rather interesting that The top 2 species that caused the most aircraft damage in terms of longitude and latitude from the multivariate plot were Mourning dove and White-tailed deer while the top 2 species that caused aircraft damage from the univariate plot were gulls and white-tailed deer.

Conclusions¶

  • From the exploratory data analysis, 69.8% of the bird strikes did not result in aircraft damage while 30.2% of the bird strikes resulted to aircraft damage.

  • The year 2018 and 2019 had the most bird strikes while 1992 had the least.

  • California had the highest aircraft damages.

  • Bird strike occur between 8-10 am and 22-23 pm.

  • Top five bird species that caused most bird strikes are mourning dove, gulls, barn swallow, european starling and horned lark while gulls, white-tailed deer, canada goose, mourning dove and red-tailed hawk caused the most aircraft damages.

  • Aircrafts with two engines were the most popular.

  • Salt Lake City, Sacramento and Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport had the most aircraft damages.

  • Summer had the most bird strikes while Fall had the most aircraft damages and winter was the season with the least that bird strikes and aircraft damages.

  • Medium sized birds caused the most aircraft damages while the small sized birds caused the most bird strikes.
